### [Enunț]

Sherlock Holmes and Dr. Watson played a game on a checkered board \( n \times n \) in size. During the game, they placed numbers on the board according to certain rules we don't know. After the game, each square of the board contains exactly one number. To determine the winner, they need to count the number of winning squares. A square is considered winning if the sum of the numbers in its column is strictly greater than the sum of the numbers in its row.

### [Abordare]

To solve this problem, we can iterate through each square on the board and compare the sum of the numbers in its column with the sum of the numbers in its row. If the sum of the column numbers is strictly greater than the sum of the row numbers, then the square is a winning square.

### [Complexitate]

O(n^2) timp, O(1) spațiu

### [Cod]
```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int n;
    cin >> n;

    for(int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        for(int j = 0; j < n; ++j) {
            int num;
            cin >> num;

            // Calculate the sum of the column numbers
            int col_sum = 0;
            for(int k = 0; k < n; ++k) {
                col_sum += num * (n - abs(k - j));
            }

            // Calculate the sum of the row numbers
            int row_sum = 0;
            for(int k = 0; k < n; ++k) {
                row_sum += num * (n - abs(i - k));
            }

            // Check if the square is winning
            if(col_sum > row_sum) {
                cout << "winning" << endl;
            } else {
                cout << "losing" << endl;
            }
        }
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This code reads the dimensions of the board and the numbers on each square. It then iterates through each square, calculates the sums of the numbers in its column and row, and determines whether it is a winning or losing square based on the comparison of these sums.

